","fields":{"standfirst":"<p>Car maker says it has briefed union representatives and its manufacturing team about the cuts at its two Victorian plants</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-02-06T03:02:28.172Z","body":"<p>Three hundred Ford workers will lose their jobs in June when the car company reduces production at its Victorian manufacturing plants as it prepares to cease manufacturing.</p><p>Ford Australia’s director of communications, Wes Sherwood, said the company briefed union representatives and its manufacturing team on Thursday morning.</p><p>\"We are continuing to match production with demand and that will mean we are reducing production by about a third in June with related job losses,\" Sherwood said.</p><p>He said the number of job losses would be in line with the level of production, meaning about 300 positions.</p><p>\"We'll continue to work with the teams to get into the exact details but it will be about 300,\" he said.</p><p>Workers at the manufacturing plants in Geelong and Broadmeadows, in Melbourne's north, will be affected.</p><p>Sherwood said the exact numbers at each site were still being worked out.</p><p>Ford announced last May that it would cease local manufacturing in October 2016, resulting in the loss of 650 jobs at its Broadmeadows plant and 510 at the Geelong plant.</p><p>At the time Ford Australia president and CEO Bob Graziano said the cost of manufacturing cars in Australia was uncompetitive.</p><p>Sherwood said Ford currently had about 1,500 salaried employees including 1,000 engineers.</p><p>He said even with it ceasing local manufacturing in 2016, the company would be Australia's biggest automotive employer, given moves by other carmakers.</p><p>\"We expect by the end of the decade to be the largest automotive employer in the country,\" he said.</p><p>Ford will manufacture its Falcon and Territory models in Victoria until 2016.</p><p>Sherwood said the carmaker was committed to its plan to transform its Australian business, which included refocusing and expanding its entire line-up for customers by 2017.</p><p>\"We are on track for the launch of our new Falcon and Territory later this year,\" he said.</p><p>Sherwood said the market was shifting towards smaller vehicles, with demand for larger cars in decline.</p><p>\"We're just going to have to match production with demand.</p><p>\"Obviously there's been some cases where others have taken some pretty aggressive action in the marketplace, really discounting their vehicles to levels that are unprecedented.\"</p><p>The Victorian attorney general, Robert Clark, said he was yet to receive details of the Ford announcement.</p><p>\"I don't have full details, but the government remains committed to support Ford workers going forward as we have to date, as indeed to support all the workers in the car industry,\" Clark said.</p>","headline":"Ford confirms 300 jobs will be cut in June as it prepares for closure","trailText":"300 jobs will be cut in June, says Fairfax Radio, as Ford prepares to stop manufacturing cars in Australia","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mgvm","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391650558036/18e19a5e-d94b-4809-a253-2be3709942ca-140x84.jpeg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391650558036/18e19a5e-d94b-4809-a253-2be3709942ca-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"387","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"429023431","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"52f2e348e4b0ab978b0f972f","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Australian Associated Press","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-06T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2039035","productionOffice":"AUS","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T01:37:51Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/feb/06