1% in 2013 with plus 2% forecast for 2014","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-02-06T00:05:40Z","body":"<p>GlaxoSmithKline almost had a good year. The qualification flows from the allegation that GSK's Chinese unit was paying bribes to doctors on a huge scale. The Chinese authorities' investigation, now eight months old, is still described as \"ongoing\" so it is impossible to guess how painful any charges, sanctions or a settlement will be, or whether the US Department for Justice and our own Serious Fraud Office will enter the fray.</p><p>The only mildly encouraging development for GSK is that the Chinese state authorities do not appear to have unofficially banned the company's medicines and vaccines. GSK's sales in China in the fourth quarter were down 29% versus 2012's level, a veritable triumph against the 61% plunge in the third quarter.</p><p>China aside, GSK's giant wheels are turning in the right direction, albeit slowly. Group turnover has stopped falling. It was minus 3% in 2011 then minus 2% in 2012 but improved 1% in 2013 with plus 2% forecast for 2014.</p><p>And one of these years chief executive Sir Andrew Witty may be able to declare that his target for return on investment in the labs has been met.</p><p>Investors in drug companies have long grumbled that billions of dollars are spent every year on research and development without any measure being taken of value for money.</p><p>Admirably, Witty tried in 2010 to counter the complaint by publishing data. GSK's rate of return has now improved to 13%, he estimates, a percentage point short of his goal.</p><p>The fruits were approvals for six major products in 2013 – including two for respiratory disease and two for melanoma. GSK can now boast that since 2009 it has had more new medicines approved in the US than any competitor.</p><p>It all helps to explain why the shares had a strong run until the Chinese scandal broke. This is a company that is managing to run slightly faster than its pate