f the ECB decided that the interest rate on the main refinancing operations and the interest rates on the marginal lending facility and the deposit facility will remain unchanged at 0.25%, 0.75% and 0.00% respectively.</p><p>The President of the ECB will comment on the considerations underlying these decisions at a press conference starting at 2.30 p.m. CET today.</p></blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-d8f9bafd-3df1-4cb5-8943-6ee6a051157f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391690387933/b0151683-3f49-4cec-ab6f-aa0ae14274d3-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Euro logo in front of European Central Bank, Frankfurt \" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Photograph: Johannes Eisele/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f38390e4b0019d0eaa7f2e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:44:06.825Z\">12.44pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/fwred/statuses/431407044935954432\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Suspense. Spannend. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ECB&amp;src=hash\">#ECB</a></p>&mdash; Frederik Ducrozet (@fwred) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/fwred/statuses/431407044935954432\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f382d5e4b0019d0eaa7f2d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:42:47.353Z\">12.42pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The European Central Bank decision is just a couple of minutes away. Over on CNBC, Danny Gabay of Fathom Consulting is arguing that the ECB should plunge into full-blown quantitative easing (<i>even though it's far from clear that this could be allowed under its mandate</i>)</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/louisabojesen/statuses/431406653183782912\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>&#39;Proper, dirty, unsterilized QE&#39;-- what the ECB should do acc to Danny Gabby, Dir, Fathom Consulting <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23QE&amp;src=hash\">#QE</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ECB&amp;src=hash\">#ECB</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CNBC\">@CNBC</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CNBCWorld\">@CNBCWorld</a></p>&mdash; Louisa Bojesen (@louisabojesen) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/louisabojesen/statuses/431406653183782912\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f3809ae4b0019d0eaa7f29\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:37:32.126Z\">12.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Anglo Irish Bank trial: jury shown share price graphs</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>Meanwhile,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/feb/03/anglo-irish-executives-irish-banking-crisis\"> one of the largest criminal trials ever held over the collapse of a financial institution</a> continued in Dublin today, as three former Anglo Irish Bank executives appeared in court for the second day.</b></p><p>From Dublin, <b>Henry McDonald </b>reports:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The crisis that was engulfing Anglo Irish Bank in the year of the 2008 financial crash forced executives to hold an unprecedented 33 board meetings in that period, a Dublin court heard today.</p><p>Natasha Mercer, a one time company secretary at the now defunct bank, told the trial of Anglo Irish bosses Sean Fitzpatrick, Patrick Whelan and Wiliam McAteer, that normally the bank held between 8 to 10 board meetings per annum.</p><p>But such was the extent of the panic infected the bank that they were meeting on average more than twice a month in 2008, the court was told.</p><p>Earlier the 15 strong jury was shown graphs on computer screens of how the shares in the bank were in \"very clear decline\" in 2008.</p><p>On St Patrick’s Day of 2008, there was a significant drop in the price to €6.95. This coincided with the failure of Bear Stearns Bank, the court heard.</p><p>But by the summer the price of a share in Anglo had fallen to €5.95. It went below €5 for the first time about July 10th.</p><p>It went back up after July 17th and hovered around the €5-€6 mark during August.</p><p>But by September 24th, the price had dropped to €3.98. It was at €2.03 on September 29th.</p><p>The Anglo Irish trio are charged with providing unlawful financial assistance to 16 named individuals in 2008 - the year the bank was later rescued by the Irish and European taxpayers.</p><p>Fitzpatrick, Whelan and McAteer pleaded not guilty to all the charges against them.</p></blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f37e20e4b0d5e31a93fef5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:24:29.547Z\">12.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Across the City, traders and economists are scampering for a quick sandwich or suchlike before the European Central Bank announces its own decision on monetary policy, in around 20 minutes (12.45pm GMT or 1.45pm Frankfurt time).</p><p><b>Ilya Spivak, c</b>urrency analyst at DailyFX, says the markets are in \"chipper mood\" ahead of the ECB's decision:<br></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The central bank is under pressure to deliver additional easing as disappointing CPI inflation data and sinking inflation expectations feed deflation fears and challenge the central bank’s mandate to maintain price stability.</p></blockquote><p>As flagged up earlier in the blog, the ECB has plenty of options -- including cutting interest rates, or imposing negative rates on bank deposits. </p><p>Another option would be to copy the Bank of England's Funding for Lending scheme, to drive down credit costs in the euro area, <b>Spivak</b> added.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:24:36.565Z\">at 12.24pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52f37cb6e4b0019d0eaa7f26\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:20:38.956Z\">12.20pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/CarolineHydeTV/statuses/431397708193345536\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>FTSE100 stays higher, £ stays lower as do UK bonds after BOE keeps rate at 0.5% &amp; asset purchases unchanged</p>&mdash; Caroline Hyde (@CarolineHydeTV) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CarolineHydeTV/statuses/431397708193345536\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f37b42e4b0d5e31a93fef4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:09:04.717Z\">12.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><b>David Kern, chief economist at the British Chambers of Commerce (BCC), says the Bank of England made the right call, and should now reshape its forward guidance on when interest rates might eventually rise:</b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>“Given the global uncertainties, and the still delicate state of the UK economy, the decision to hold both interest rates and QE was uncontroversial and appropriate. As British business has enjoyed the added stability and confidence that has come with the forward guidance policy, the speculation favouring an early interest rate rise is unhelpful and potentially damaging for the economy.</p><p>“While the essence of the forward guidance strategy is to reassure businesses that interest rates will be kept as low as economic conditions will allow, the MPC should use next week’s Inflation Report to place its policy on firmer foundations. Linking forward guidance exclusively to unemployment has proved counter-productive. Focusing instead on a range of key indicators would increase its effectiveness, reinforce business confidence, and pour cold water on the cynicism that many city analysts have demonstrated.</p></blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:10:52.637Z\">at 12.10pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52f37a1ae4b0019d0eaa7f22\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T12:08:23.812Z\">12.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's some instant reaction to the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/blog/2014/feb/06/european-central-bank-rate-decision-mario-draghi-bank-of-england-business-live#block-52f37905e4b0d5e31a93feed\">Bank of England's no-change in interest rate</a>s, and no statement on monetary policy:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/notayesmansecon/statuses/431397907971842048\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>The Bank of England announcement means that the UK will soon have (5th March) five years of an &quot;emergency&quot; base rate of 0.5% <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23BoE&amp;src=hash\">#BoE</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23GBP&amp;src=hash\">#GBP</a></p>&mdash; Shaun Richards (@notayesmansecon) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/notayesmansecon/statuses/431397907971842048\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/EdConwaySky/statuses/431397674336911361\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>No change &amp; no statement from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bankofengland\">@bankofengland</a> means Inflation Report next Wed is the key moment to find out what happens to forward guidance</p>&mdash; Ed Conway (@EdConwaySky) <a hr